Contributed by Henry JakubowskiProfessor Chemistry at College of St BenedictSt Johns University Contributors and Attributions Learning Objectives identify the types of catalysis used in enzymecatalyzed reactions given a detailed mechanism interpret kinetic experiments experiments varying substrate inhibitors pH ion strength and amino acid side chains through chemical modification or sitespecific mutagenesis to better understand the catalytic mechanisms utilized in enzymecatalyzed reactions identify potential rate limiting steps in enzyme catalyzed reaction mechanisms and simplify kinetic equations based on them generally describe the diversity the critical active site residues and the biological activities of proteases describe the structurefunction of the proteasome We can apply what we learned about catalysis by small molecules to enzymecatalyzed reactions To understand the mechanism of an enzymecatalyzed reaction we try to alter as many variables one at a time and ascertain the effects of the changes on the activity of the enzyme Kinetic methods can be used to obtain data from which inferences about the mechanism can be made Obviously crystal structures of the enzyme in the presence and absence of a competitive inhibitor give abundant information about possible mechanisms Topic hierarchy Contributors and Attributions Prof Henry Jakubowski College of St BenedictSt Johns University